<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-329-126  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 329 126.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computing Canada  May 11 1989 v15 n10 p43(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Taking small logical CIM steps towards big gains. (GandalfTechnologies implements computer-integrated manufacturing)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Manship, Roger.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>A first and effective step towards computer-integratedmanufacturing (CIM) is the assessment and linking of currentcomputer resources, as is exemplified by Ottawa, Canada's GandalfTechnologies.andP;  Gandalf used computers in many areas of planning,software design, production control, manufacturing, and repair.andO;These were effectively self-contained islands of automation.andP;  Thefirm decided to integrate the diverse systems by way of aStarmaster Starport local area network (LAN).andP;  Production programscan now be designed on and transferred from microcomputers toproduction systems, with work-in-progress data transferred overthe LAN to shop supervisors and other personnel.andP;  Gandalf espousesfour tenets for CIM implementation: keep it simple, applyautomation only when appropriate, use proven technology, and putas much technology in the hands of users as possible.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Gandalf Technologies Inc. (automation).andO;Topic:     Computer-Integrated ManufacturingImplementationCase StudyAutomation.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>